&#xa0;
[normal]Written evidence submitted by the Energy Networks Association (HOT59)[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Energy Networks Association (ENA) welcomes the opportunity to provide written evidence to the Energy and Climate Change Committee’s Inquiry on Heat.  
[normal]ENA is the voice of the networks representing the ‘wires and pipes’ transmission and distribution network 
[normal]operators for gas and electricity in the UK and Ireland. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]ENA’s role is to represent the interests of our members at home and in Europe. Through our work we aim to deliver the most supportive environment for investment and development of the energy networ
[normal]ks of the future.  ENA's overriding goals are to promote the UK and Ireland energy networks and enable our networks to be the safest, most reliable, most efficient and sustainable in the world.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]ENA is in a unique position to address the needs for a balanc
[normal]ed solution as it represents both electricity and gas network operators.  Through our various work streams our members are considering the different scenarios needed to meet the 2020 and 2050 targets, and how the electricity and gas networks could be trans
[normal]formed as a result.  For examples ENA coordinates the sharing of learning from the Low Carbon Network Fund projects for our members that are addressing the challenge of an all electric future.  At the same time our Gas Futures Group are undertaking a study
[normal] to look at the future of domestic heating.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Most recently, ENA has commissioned Delta-ee to carry out a study to look at 2050 Pathways for Domestic Heat.  This study, which was published in October 2012, demonstrates that by 
[normal]keeping a variety of options o
[normal]pen to decarbonise heat gives lower risks, and potentially a lower cost path that pursuing a narrower end point. 
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Is the government taking the right approach to reduce heat energy demand?[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]ENA and its members believe that while the Department of Energy and Climate Change (DECC) has made significant progress in its approach to reducing heat demand, with the introduction of the Green Deal, the roll out of smart meters and the Energy Companies 
[normal]Obligation, there is far more that can be achieved in this sector. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]In 2012 the ENA Gas Futures Group commissioned Delta-ee to analyse the UK’s housing stock in a detailed way looking at how the various heating technologies currently available could be ef
[normal]fectively deployed.  It remains the most comprehensive domestic heat study ever undertaken, and built on the Redpoint work ENA published in 2010.  In this study, it is assumed that there is a 21% reduction in thermal demand through the measures mentioned a
[normal]bove. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]If the UK is to meet its carbon targets, reduction of this level are essential and ENA members believe that energy efficiency measures should be the immediate focus for DECC, as it is the single biggest and most cost efficient change that can reduc
[normal]e heat demand and therefore carbon.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The Green Deal and ECO are the two policies going forward focused on the uptake of insulation measures.  However, it is unlikely that these will deliver the required uptake without being supported by a robust framewor
[normal]k of policies, including policies such as Building Regulations. The introduction of smart meters presents an opportunity for customers to engage with their energy usage and therefore better manage their heating systems.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]What progress is the government [bold]making on reducing the demand for heat?[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]ENA members believe that DECC has laid the foundations for the required heat demand reduction with the Green Deal and ECO. However, consumer engagement is only likely to improve where there is a robust framework for
[normal] these policies, and that the consumers are informed to such a level that they are able to see benefits, in opting for such measures through incentives and regulation.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Biomass is deemed a key fuel for heat production from both the cost and GHG perspective[bold]s.[bold]&#xa0;[bold] What should be done to ensure methods of calculating biomass GHG balance represent an accurate picture?[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]As highlighted in the Delta-ee study, biomass pellet boilers are a mature technology, although product and supply chains in the UK are only just em
[normal]erging. However, strong growth in this sector could lead to cost reductions for this technology.  The most significant challenge for future biomass uptake remains customer perceptions, as currently biomass performs poorly in consumer research.  Any future 
[normal]uptake will also be highly dependent on the security of fuel supply due to competition for resources with transport and larger generation and the development of a UK supply chain. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]ENA members recommend that DECC continues to engage with the key stakehold
[normal]ers in this area to ensure that the methods used for calculation of the biomass/GHG balance are developed in accordance to set standards.
[normal]There are sustainability guidelines for biomass, do these go far enough?[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]ENA members support the existing 
[normal]sustainability guidelines for biomass and believe that these should be regularly reviewed to ensure they remain appropriate as this market develops.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]What will the local environmental impact (for example air pollution) be from the use heat generation in ur[bold]ban areas, for example CHP units?[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]When CHP units are powered by biomass, these units produce more particulate emissions than gas fired CHP. There is also a potential issue with the required vehicle movements in urban locations and the associated pollution
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]What are the relative merits of using gas to directly provide space heating compared to centralised electricity production plus domestic heat pumps?[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]The ENA/Delta-ee study looked at the merits of a balanced approach towards low carbon heating. It 
[normal]examined three basic scenarios for the future of heating in the UK:
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Customer Choice[bold] – which 
[normal]allows customers to choose, based on upfront cost, running cost and fit with the housing stock: 
[normal]Carbon reduction targets for the residential sector will not be met
[normal] by a combination of reducing thermal demand and allowing customers to chose their heating appliance (without government intervention). Even when strong progress is made on low carbon heating appliance cost and performance, and with 75 TWh of biomethane, c
[normal]arbon reductions (2040-50 compared to 2010-20) of 46% are achieved. Gas boilers continue to be used in 19 million homes, based on their low capital and running costs, and excellent fit with UK homes. 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Electrification and Heat Networks[bold] – which 
[normal]assumes 
[normal]virt
[normal]ually all homes use either electric heating 
[normal](heat pumps &amp; direct electric) 
[normal]or heat networks, fed-by zero carbon heat
[normal]. There is no role for gas. This predicts 96% reduction in carbon emissions (from 2010-20 levels). 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Balanced Transition[bold] - 
[normal]has an approximat
[normal]ely even split across three heating types: 
[normal](1) heat networks 
[normal](dense urban areas &amp; new build), 
[normal](2) low carbon gas appliances 
[normal](suburbia), 
[normal](3) electric heating 
[normal](some suburbia, rural and new build). This includes 75TWh of biomethane and a 90% reduction in carb
[normal]on emissions 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The Report makes clear that the Balanced Transition scenario can be achieved with less government intervention (and at less cost to the customer) than Electrification &amp; Heat Networks (E&amp;HN), while achieving 90% carbon reduction from today to
[normal] 2050:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]High efficiency gas appliances
[normal] (including hybrid gas boiler using air source heat pumps),
[normal] have lower running costs (and in some cases upfront costs) for certain parts of the housing stock 
[normal]than electric alternatives and are easier to retrofit into e
[normal]xisting homes with gas boilers.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]A greater mix of technologies has a lower impact on the energy system
[normal]. The addition of hybrid heat pumps and gas appliances to the mix reduces additional peak electricity generation demand by 50% lower than E&amp;HN, and distri
[normal]ct heat is focused on higher density housing.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The benefits of a Balanced Transition approach are that it achieves a 90% carbon reduction from today to 2050 and it:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]DECC has recently indicated its interest in hydrogen and ENA’s members are eager to explore these issues further. Members have submitted bids into the Network Innovation Competition process involving the developm
[normal]ent of hydrogen projects and also the gasification of waste. Both these potential technologies will, if commercially viable, contribute to decarbonising heat in the UK while continuing to make use of the existing gas distribution system.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Why is community [bold]heating/CHP not more common in the UK?[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]District heating is a mature and widespread concept in several EU markets, but there is minimal UK penetration.  Whilst there has been development in district heat in the UK since 1950 (with the majority being develo
[normal]ped in the 1960’s) still only 1-2% of UK heat demand is met by the technology.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]This is largely due to the discovery of North Sea gas and subsequent investment in gas networks which makes gas available as a fuel to c. 80% of all households in the UK
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]With 
[normal]regard to the physical fit of district heating in UK homes, there is technically no restriction on the housing type; however the ease of fitting a heat interface unit (HIU) inside the house to the heat “main” can be challenging in retrofit.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Economically, 
[normal]district heating is highly sensitive to discount rates and the relevant amortisation period, and currently the costs in the UK are much higher than continental Europe.  However there is a potential for UK costs to fall if there were to be large growth in d
[normal]istrict heating.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Consumer perception of district heating is limited due to a lack of understanding or awareness of this technology. Therefore there is no strong consumer opinion on the pros/cons of domestic heating as a low carbon technology.  Due to the 
[normal]current lack of regulation in this sector there are possible concerns over consumers being “tied in” to long-term contracts and a perceived “loss” of freedom of choice for their heating.  Using district heating requires the minimal change in consumer behav
[normal]iour, as the interface and controls function like a boiler and connect to an existing system. Indeed there is evidence of high customer satisfaction once connected.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]It is important to note that district heating is only low carbon when the fuel used to gen
[normal]erate the heat is also low carbon.
