[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The ENA/Delta-ee report methodology developed a residential heat model that combines the following in order to assess the 
[normal]optimal appliance technology pathways, by property type, based on known/emerging heating technology, required to meet carbon and renew
[normal]able targets, highlighting the impact on consumers (cost to change and behavioural) and the potential load changes on the gas and electricity distribution networks out to 2050
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]The report contains:[bold]&#xa0;[bold]A housing stock model[bold] dividing the UK housing stock into 
[normal]35 segments according to fuel availability and use, age, and building type. For each segment the thermal demand and how this changes decade by decade to 2050 is defined. 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]A technology performance model[bold]: which forecasts future cost and performance– coverin
[normal]g: gas boiler; gas heat pump; low electrical efficiency micro-CHP; high electrical efficiency micro-CHP; gas boiler + solar thermal; air source heat pump; ground source heat pump; hybrid gas boiler + air source heat pump; biomass boiler; district heating; 
[normal]direct electric (storage) heating. 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]A customer choice model[bold] that incorporates the physical fit of different technologies with different parts of the housing stock; customer uptake based on payback and upfront cost; and customer attitudes to different technologies. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]This in turn led to the development of three 
[normal]basic scenarios: Customer Choice; Electrification and Heat Networks; and Balanced Transition.
[normal]&#xa0;
